  "prompt": "Does Google take into account that you are speeding while calculating your ETA?",
  "response": "Yes, Google Maps takes into account typical traffic patterns and speeds when calculating estimated time of arrival (ETA). However, it does not actively track whether you are speeding or not. Instead, it provides ETA predictions based on the average travel speeds for different types of roads and current traffic conditions. \n\nIf you are driving faster than the average speed, you may arrive sooner than the ETA suggested. Conversely, if you are driving slower, you may take longer. The ETA can also be adjusted dynamically based on real-time data, such as traffic jams or road conditions, but does not factor in individual driving behavior like speeding.",
